 href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: North Korea gives US the finger</span><hr size=1> Anika said her numbers were completely unscientific.  She's not implying they're some rigorously derived numbers.  Also, I believe she said in the next 40 years, and you talked about  in the next 10.  I didn't even put a number on it, I just said &quot;likely.&quot;  There are some things that you cannot get an accurate percentage chance for.  It's just not a number you can derive through any logical process.<br>
<br>
I agree with you that there is close to a 0% chance of a sovereign nation attacking the US in the next 10 years.  Anika and I aren't even worried about that, we are worried about terrorists.<br>
<br>
We are worried about NK because we believe (and history would support us) that NK will sell weapons to terrorists for the right price.<br>
<br>
Overall, I think the world has already forgotten 9/11.  They are back to their way of thinking that everything will just be ok and we don't have to think about the rest of the world.  I think it will maybe take a disaster like nuclear holocaust to wake people up and realize how serious the terrorist threat is.<br>
<br>
I think if you really perceive just how dangerous that threat is, you are inclined to be much more tolerant of President Bush and his efforts to fight it.  Some of us believe that this is the greatest threat our country has ever faced, and no level of effort we put forth to contain it will be sufficient.  Essentially, anything that Bush wants to do to hinder terrorism is ok with me.  People worry about a few soldiers dying.  That sounds bad, but it doesn't sound like much when you compare it to the 20 million people that would die in a day if a nuclear bomb were detonated in NYC.  I for one believe that those that oppose Bush simply do not comprehend the magnitude of the threat.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=anikacrystalwind>Anika Crystalwind</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Admin Gnome</span><br>  Posts: 1892<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/4/03 11:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=23>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.cinci.rr.com/twagers/02.jpg width=90 height=88></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: Hmmm</span><hr size=1> Clarification. <br>
<br>
As Amm said, I was looking over the next 40 years.  I don't think, unless a radical power-shift in the world occurs, that any soverign nation would be foolish enough to attack us directly.  With the massive military advantage we have now, and extrapolated out over the near future, that nation would be basically signing a death warrant for itself.  Don't see it as a factor.<br>
<br>
However, someone, somewhere will probably manage to set off a nuclear device.  I listed 4 cities as likely targets because:<br>
<br>
1)  NYC, obvious target.<br>
2)  Washington DC, again, obvious target.<br>
3)  LA, as the 'entertainment capital' of the US, many people will see that as the source of the 'filth and perversion' that the US is spreading across the world via movies and television programs.  <br>
4)  Seattle/Redmond.  Huge port area, close to an unprotected border, and home of a company that largely signifies the pinnacle of capitalism, more or less.  <br>
<br>
If I had listed a 5th, it would be Las Vegas, due to the same reasons as LA.  Another dangerous place, and perhaps one of the most damaging from a terror standpoint, would be someplace like Disneyland.  Talk about sending a message.<br>
<br>
Anyway, it's not something to hide in a closet and cower in fear over.  Odds are when it happens, they will have been little if nothing we could have done to prevent it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rathic>Rathic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/6/03 1:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> lol...</span><hr size=1> i find this conversation very intersting... being that i am a nuclear weapons maintainer for the USAF <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   if i were u all, id be more worried about mysteriously empty russian stockpiles, than i am about NK. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
